The domain ‚Ñ¶ is a vertical square cylinder bounded by a rigid wall, with gravity in the ‚àíy
direction. The size of ‚Ñ¶ is (L‚Ñ¶ , H‚Ñ¶ ) = (4d, 10d), where d is the initial bubble diameter, L‚Ñ¶ is
the square side and H‚Ñ¶ is the cylinder height. ‚Ñ¶ is discretized by 10.24 √ó 106 hexahedral control
volumes distributed on 512 processors, whereas the grid size is h = d/40. As initial condition,
both bubbles and liquid are quiescent. Boundary conditions are non-slip at the rigid wall and
periodic on the streamwise (y-direction). Thus, bubbles go out of ‚Ñ¶ on the top boundary, and
they come back in ‚Ñ¶ again from the opposite boundary.
Two bubbles are initially released with configuration angles Œ∏0 = {0o, 45o , 90o }, and centroidcentroid distance 1.5d. Figure 2 shows the time evolution of Reynolds number, configuration
angle Œ∏(t) between ‚àÜx1,2 = x2 ‚àí x1 and its projection on the plane x ‚àí z, and dimensionless
separation distance between the bubbles, s = ||x2 ‚àí x1 ||/d, for Œ∏0 = {0o , 45o , 90o }. Due to the
buoyancy force, the bubbles move upward, while bubble-bubble interaction produces oscillatory
trajectories, as illustrated in Fig. 2 for s(t) and Œ∏(t). The deformable bubbles tend to move
up to the wall, but they do not collide against the wall, where a bouncing effect is observed.
Furthermore, Œ∏ decreases as the time advances for Œ∏0 = {45o, 90o }, indicating that two bubbles
tend to align side-by-side, due to a torque action between their centroids, as shown in Fig. 3.
It is observed that a pair of deformable bubbles repel each other for Œ∏0 = {0o , 45o }, whereas
they reproduce the drafting-kissing-tumbling (DKT) phenomenon for Œ∏0 = 90o (Fig. 3). In the
drafting stage, the trailing bubble moves faster than the leading one, indeed, they approach
closer. Then, in the kissing stage, bubbles almost touch each other and the gap between them
is less than the grid size h. In the tumbling stage, a rotating effect between bubble centroids is
observed, whereas the bubbles begin to separate each other, as illustrated in Fig. 3.
